  "prompt": "Was there welfare during the Anglo-Saxon era?",
  "response": "During the Anglo-Saxon era in England (approximately 5th to 11th centuries), the concept of welfare as we understand it today did not exist. However, there were informal social support systems in place that provided assistance to individuals and families in need. \n\nThe Anglo-Saxon society was largely agrarian and community-oriented, and local communities often looked after their own members. This responsibility might include care for the elderly, sick, or disabled within the community. Extended families played a crucial role in providing support, and local systems of charity and aid existed, often organized by the church.\n\nChurches and monasteries were also significant sources of aid, as they would occasionally provide food, shelter, and care for the poor and needy. The concept of *almsgiving* was important, and charitable acts were considered a moral duty for Christians.\n\nWhile there were no structured welfare programs like those developed later in history, these community-based and church-related supports functioned as informal safety nets for those in need during the Anglo-Saxon period.",
